# Global Distribution

Multi-region configuration enables low-latency reads globally and disaster recovery. Consistency choices impact both performance and data guarantees.

## Configure multi-region writes

Enable multi-region writes for active-active deployments where each region can accept writes.

```csharp
// Enable in account settings (Azure portal or CLI)
// az cosmosdb update --enable-multiple-write-locations true

// SDK configuration
var options = new CosmosClientOptions
{
    ApplicationPreferredRegions = new List<string>
    {
        Regions.EastUS,     // Local region
        Regions.WestEurope  // Secondary
    }
};
// With multi-region writes, the SDK routes writes to the nearest region
```

Trade-offs:
- Lower write latency (writes go to nearest region)
- Requires conflict resolution policy
- Higher cost (billed per region for writes)

## Choose appropriate consistency level

Five levels from strongest to weakest:

| Level | Guarantee | Use case |
|-------|-----------|----------|
| **Strong** | Linearizable reads | Financial transactions |
| **Bounded Staleness** | Reads lag by K versions or T time | Leaderboards, counts |
| **Session** (default) | Read-your-own-writes | Most applications |
| **Consistent Prefix** | No out-of-order reads | Social feeds |
| **Eventual** | No ordering guarantee | Counters, likes |

```csharp
// Account-level default
// Set in Azure portal: Account → Default Consistency

// Per-request override (can only weaken, not strengthen)
var options = new ItemRequestOptions
{
    ConsistencyLevel = ConsistencyLevel.Eventual  // Weaker = lower RU cost
};
```

**Session consistency** is the best default for most applications — it guarantees you can always read what you just wrote.

## Add read regions near users

Add read replicas in regions closest to your users for low-latency reads.

```csharp
// Configure preferred regions in order of priority
var options = new CosmosClientOptions
{
    ApplicationPreferredRegions = new List<string>
    {
        Regions.WestEurope,  // European users read from here
        Regions.EastUS       // Fallback
    }
};
// Reads automatically route to the closest available region
```

## Configure automatic failover

Enable automatic failover so Cosmos DB redirects traffic during regional outages.

```bash
# Enable automatic failover
az cosmosdb update \
    --name myCosmosAccount \
    --resource-group myRG \
    --enable-automatic-failover true

# Set failover priorities
az cosmosdb failover-priority-change \
    --name myCosmosAccount \
    --resource-group myRG \
    --failover-policies "East US=0" "West US=1" "West Europe=2"
```

## Implement conflict resolution

Required for multi-region writes. Choose a strategy:

- **Last Writer Wins (LWW)**: Default. Uses `_ts` or a custom path. Higher timestamp wins.
- **Custom**: Use a stored procedure or merge procedure for complex logic.

```csharp
// Last Writer Wins with custom path
var containerProperties = new ContainerProperties("orders", "/customerId")
{
    ConflictResolutionPolicy = new ConflictResolutionPolicy
    {
        Mode = ConflictResolutionMode.LastWriterWins,
        ResolutionPath = "/lastModified"  // Custom timestamp field
    }
};
```

## Configure zone redundancy

Enable availability zone redundancy for resilience within a region.

```bash
# Enable zone redundancy (only at account creation or when adding regions)
az cosmosdb update \
    --name myCosmosAccount \
    --resource-group myRG \
    --locations regionName="East US" isZoneRedundant=true failoverPriority=0
```

Zone redundancy provides:
- Automatic replication across 3+ availability zones
- No downtime during single-zone failures
- No additional cost (included)

